What happened to the electric mail trucks? Theyâ€™re way behind schedule. A multibillion-dollar program to buy electric vehicles for the U.S. Postal Service is far behind its original schedule, plagued by manufacturing mishaps and supplier infighting that threaten a cornerstone of outgoing President Joe Bidenâ€™s fight against climate change. The Postal Service is slated to purchase 60,000 â€œNext Generation Delivery Vehicles,â€ or NGDVs â€” mostly electric â€” from defense contractor Oshkosh, which has a long history of producing military and heavy industrial vehicles, but not postal trucks. Congress provided $3 billion for the nearly $10 billion project in the 2022 Inflation Reduction Act, one of Bidenâ€™s chief legislative accomplishments. But as of November, the Postal Service had received only 93 of the Oshkosh trucks, the agency told The Washington Post â€” far fewer than the 3,000 expected by now. Significant manufacturing difficulties that were not disclosed to the Postal Service for more than a year have stymied production, according to internal company records and four people with knowledge of the events, speaking on the condition of anonymity to avoid professional reprisals. Could MORE Chinese products be banned?! A combination of unique factors has put some Chinese technologies on U.S. lawmakersâ€™ naughty list. Companies from China are increasingly global technology trendsetters, including in important areas like electric vehicles and artificial intelligence. Itâ€™s hard to buy an internet-connected home device that doesnâ€™t run on Chinese technology. Technologies that originate in other countries considered adversaries of the United States, such as Iran and Russia, are mostly irrelevant in the United States. Thereâ€™s also a fuzzy line in China between private corporations and the government. U.S. officials believe that TikTok or other Chinese companies would have to comply if Beijing ordered them to hand over data they have on Americans, to spy on us, or to spread Chinese Communist Party propaganda.

A judge rejected the sale of InfoWars to The Onion (12/11/2024). U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Christopher Lopez ruled Tuesday that the November court-ordered auction of Jonesâ€™s website lacked transparency. The decision capped a two-day hearing that stretched late into the night in U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Christopher Lopezâ€™s Houston courtroom. â€œI donâ€™t think anyone acted in bad faith here. I think everyone was trying to buy an asset and put their best foot forward and play by the rules,â€ Lopez said as he delivered his decision. The judge took issue with the lack of transparency from the sealed bidding process selected byÂ the court-appointed trustee Christopher Murray, who was overseeing the sale of Jonesâ€™s assets. The judge added that he was troubled that the process, however well intended, â€œdid not maximize value in any way, based on the record before me.â€ In aÂ statement, the Onionâ€™s CEO, Ben Collins, expressed disappointment that the ruling did not clear a path forward for any bidder, but he indicated it would continue its efforts toward acquiring Infowars. â€œIt is part of our larger mission to make a better, funnier internet, regardless of the outcome,â€ the statement said. The Murdoch family is fighting over future control of Fox News and the Wall Street Journal. Rupert Murdoch wanted to change the terms of his familyâ€™s trust to ensure that his son Lachlan would be his successor upon his death, but a Nevada probate commissioner rejected his bid. Murdoch, 93, initiated the effort to change the terms of the trust last year to preserve the conservative orientation of his sprawling media empire. As first reported by the New York Times this summer, the elder Murdoch was concerned that a â€œlack of consensusâ€ among his three other older children would have financial consequences for the company. But probate commissioner Edmund â€œJoeâ€ Gorman Jr. ruled against the effort, deeming it a â€œcarefully crafted charade,â€Â the New York Times reported on Monday afternoon.Â The case will now move to a district judge who could choose to affirm the recommendation, deny it or send it back for additional inquiry. According to aÂ complaint made public Tuesday, police think Mangione is the person who killed Thompson based on evidence that includes â€œwritten admissions about the crimeâ€ as well as surveillance footage. Mangione, who was arraigned in a courthouse near Altoona, Pennsylvania, faces five counts in that state, including carrying a firearm without a license, possessing instruments of a crime and providing law enforcement with false identification. The m*rder count and other charges were filed in New York.

Trumps BIG budget plans President-elect Donald Trump this week tapped Musk and former GOP presidential candidate Vivek Ramaswamy to stand up a commission to make recommendations by 2026 for cutting government spending and regulation. Dubbed the â€œDepartment of Government Efficiency,â€ or DOGE, the commissionâ€™s structure and specific goals are not yet clear. (Under current law, only Congress can actually cut spending. Trumpâ€™s team is exploring how it could implement some DOGE recommendations without congressional approval, The Washington Post reported this week.)Musk has publicly sparred with agencies over the years, including those that have taken actions against his businesses. For example, this week he elevated a call for â€œdefangingâ€ both the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Federal Trade Commission, an agency he has accused of â€œoverreachâ€ and being â€œweaponiz[ed] â€¦ for censorship & political machinations.â€

The EPA has announced a ban of two known carcinogens used in a variety of consumer products and industrial settings. The new rules underscore President Joe Bidenâ€™s efforts to enact key protections against harmful chemicals before leaving office.

The fall of Syrian President Bashar al-Assadâ€™s government signals a time of uncertainty for Syrians and the Middle East, NATO Secretary General Mark Rutte said in a statement Monday. He called on rebel leaders to â€œuphold the rule of law, protect civilians and respect religious minorities.â€ â€œRussia and Iran were the main backers of the Assad regime, and they share the responsibility for the crimes committed against the Syrian people,â€ he said. TheÂ lightning advance of rebels, culminating in theÂ fall of DamascusÂ early Sunday, saw prison guards abandon their posts in cities from north to south. Now, Syrians are bracing to learn who among the countryâ€™s more thanÂ 100,000 unaccounted-for detaineesÂ are still alive. Caption from articles by Kelsey Baker, Louisa LoveluckÂ andÂ Mustafa Salim.

Amateur internet sleuths are racing to identify the gunman who killed the chief of the nationâ€™s largest health insurer in midtown Manhattan on Wednesday, hoping to piece together clues and beat police investigators at their own high-profile manhunt. The shooter seemingly vanished after being caught on video in one of the worldâ€™s most surveilled cities, offering an online community of wannabe detectives a tantalizing case. They pored over street footage and digital data toÂ guess his brand of backpack,Â debate how he had silenced his pistolÂ andÂ scrutinize his getaway bike. But they are being confronted online by a rival movement: users who have lionized the gunman over an unconfirmed belief that the killing was an act of rage over the health insurance industry. They have shared memes branding the shooter as a â€œfolk heroâ€ and warned digital vigilantes not to track him down. â€œAnyone who helps to identify the shooter is an enemy of the people,â€ said one post on X with 39,000 likes. Caption from article by Drew Harwell,Â Caitlin GilbertÂ andÂ Douglas MacMillan.

French President Emmanuel Macron pledged Thursday that he would name a new prime minister within days, railed against the far-right and left factions that brought down the government and ruled out resigning early himself. The president promised to tap a candidate â€œin the coming days,â€ after Prime Minister Michel Barnierâ€™s government became the first to be toppled by a no-confidence vote in six decades. It will be tricky to find a candidate who could command enough support from lawmakers in a bitterly polarized landscape.

Word of the year: Brain rot Oxfordâ€™s 2024 Word of the Year is more than a century old, but that doesnâ€™t mean itâ€™s not incredibly relevant in 2024. The winner, announced on Monday by the University of Oxford, was â€œbrain rotâ€ â€” a term that describes the overconsumption of material or content to the point that it deteriorates oneâ€™s mental state. (As in, how sludgy you feel after bingeing an entire Netflix show after â€” or while â€” doomscrolling.)According to Oxford, the word was first used in 1854 in Henry David Thoreauâ€™s book â€œWalden.â€ But in 2024, the term is finding a new meaning as people are surrounded by scrolling their phones, notifications and memes. The word, according to Oxford, has seen a 230 percent increase in usage between 2023 and 2024.But who decides what is the word of the year? Many dictionary organizations have issued their pronouncements this month, and multiple have honored words originating on and popularized by social media and our changing language, experts said.

South Korea had martial law for six hours Tuesday night. The countryâ€™s deeply unpopular president, Yoon Suk Yeol, stunned the nation Tuesday by declaring â€œemergency martial lawâ€ â€” a risky power play that launched an extraordinary six hours of turmoil and evoked the military dictatorships that many South Koreans believed had been consigned to the history books. Yoonâ€™s decree, made in a televised announcement late Tuesday night as he accused the opposition of â€œantistateâ€ activities, prompted thousands of protesters demanding a return to democratic government to gather outside the National Assembly, where lawmakers convened urgently to overturn the order. With police officers forming a barricade around the parliamentary complex, some opposition lawmakers even climbed through windows to get into the voting chamber. Before dawn Wednesday morning, Yoon said he wouldÂ lift martial lawÂ in line with the parliamentary vote and withdraw troops from the streets. He capped off his remarks with one last reference to â€œantistateâ€ activities, though it came off more like an afterthought than a justification to take military control of the country. The political roller-coaster was extreme even by the standards of South Korea, where deep polarization and combative politics often lead to dramatic power moves and countermoves. Caption from article by Michelle Ye Hee Lee

Global talks to forge a landmark treaty aimed at reducing plastic pollution broke down after negotiators from more than 170 countries remained deadlocked over how to curb the worldâ€™s growing mountain of plastic waste.

dig into the real Bob Dylan you know the one behind the harmonica and the poetry the one that dated muses got married in secret and pulled out a surprise divorce kid out of nowhere so buckle up buttercups it's about to get messy before Bob Dylan became Bob Dylan he was Bobby Zimmerman from Minnesota and Echo Helstrom was the it girl of hiving high school Echo was the blueprint of the bohemian type women that he would surround himself with later and many believe she was the inspiration for some of his early music fast forward to Greenwich Village in the early 60s where Bob meets Suze Rotolo the woman who will forever be immortalized on the cover of his Freewheelinâ€™ album Suze was an artist and a political activist who introduced Bob to leftist politics which influenced his music in the film Elle Fanning is playing a character named Sylvie which is based on Suze can you see it their relationship was passionate but very messy Bob's career was taking off and he had a wandering eye enter folk singer Joan Baez she was already successful with her own album and she invited Bob to perform with her they started bumping uglies but soon he began to treat her like she was extra baggage she said he was demoralizing and they broke up later he apologized to her and they began performing together again I think we're gonna see this dynamic in the film as well by the mid 60s Bob's career is on fire and so is his love life enter Sara Lownds Sara was a former Playboy Bunny and a single mom they got married in 1965 Bob adopted her first daughter Maria and together they had four children three boys one girl Jesse Dylan who is a filmmaker daughter Anna Dylan who unlike some of her brothers is living more of a private life Sam Dylan who also stays a bit more private and then we've got Jakob Dylan also a singer and a songwriter lead vocalist of the Wallflowers who to me looks like a cuter version of his dad Bob and Sara were together for 12 years they grew apart he cheated on her they got divorced and Bob was doing his thing Bob was in a relationship with a woman named Ruth Tyrangiel this could be her or that could be her all I know is they were together for about 17 years and she was considered his common law wife here's where things get messy because around the same time he was in a relationship with his backup singer named Carolyn Dennis together they had a daughter they named Desiree and then they got married in secret no one knew about it until they filed for divorce no one knew they had another daughter Carolyn said they purposely left his last name off of the birth certificate so that Desiree could decide to add it if she wanted to later she also said that implying that he kept Desiree a secret was a huge insult and that he was a great voice_to_text: my heart felt physical pain watching this tears streaming down my face Super/Man the Christopher Reeve Story maybe I'm late to the game watching this 10/10 cannot recommend enough we learned about his parents how he grew up he went to Cornell then he went to Juilliard here he met Robin Williams they had a lifelong friendship boom he's hired for Superman the hottest Clark Kent he's filming in London where he meets Gae Exton they begin a relationship because his parentsâ€™ relationship was not a great example Christopher could not commit but he was living in London with Gae together they had two children son Matthew and daughter Alexandra Christopher is busier and busier doing Superman's 1 2 3 and 4 in 1987 Gae and Christopher decide to separate he moves back to the US and he sees his children on holidays later that same year Christopher meets a young singer actress named Dana Morosini they were a couple living together but again Christopher had commitment issues Christopher was Superman he was 6â€™4 buff athletic very physical he was a pilot he wind surfed sailed boats he learned how to ride horses for a project he was in even though he was allergic after about five years Christopher finally decided to propose to Dana and they got married in 1992 later that same year they had a son they named William in this documentary they talk about the tragic accident that happened in 1995 he was competing at a horse show when right before the third jump his horse just refused completely stopped Christopher was thrown off the horse fell directly on his head broken snapped just like a noose half an inch to the left he would have been gone half an inch to the right he would have just gotten up his first and second vertebrae completely destroyed his spinal cord was severely damaged he was paralyzed from the neck down could not breathe without a ventilator this documentary talks about how his own mother wanted to pull the plug and he wanted to unalive himself he didn't wanna go on any longer but Dana looked into his eyes told him she was never going anywhere and said you are still you and I love you listen tears are gonna stream down your face and then they talk about how Robin Williams went to the hospital to go visit him made him laugh the entire world wanted to know what happened to Christopher because he almost did not make it and with the help of Robin Williams and his wife and Christopher's wife Dana Christopher Reeve was able to make an appearance at the 1996 Oscars watching this reminded me to be grateful for your health for all of the little things does anyone remember this Super Bowl commercial from the year 2000 where Christopher Reeve looked like he was walking on his own two feet my jaw was on the floor and then come to find out it wasn't real it was just a commercial for some *investment* company I was bawling tears even looking at this I wanna cry Christopher Reeve was only 52 when he passed away in 2004 from cardiac arrest less than a year later his wife Dana was diagnosed with lung cancer even though she never smoked a year and a half after Christopher passed away Dana passed away leaving Will without parents at 13 years old this was so well done I'm still recovering his children are gorgeous and Will  is on Good Morning America to make your heart ache even more someone in this film says if Christopher was still alive Robin still would be too
